        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer902768815" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8567069137383806501">I enjoyed Orfeo fairly well because I majored in music and therefore studied many of the composers and pieces mentioned in the book. But frankly I&apos;d be curious how comprehensible it would be to someone unfamiliar with the history of 20th century art music. It reads like one long inside joke for composition students. <br/><br/>The book&apos;s strong points are its description of musical pieces (in particular I liked the multi page mediation on Reich&apos;s Psalm) and the story of Peter Els and his various loves thro</span>
  <span id="freeText8567069137383806501" style="display:none">I enjoyed Orfeo fairly well because I majored in music and therefore studied many of the composers and pieces mentioned in the book. But frankly I'd be curious how comprehensible it would be to someone unfamiliar with the history of 20th century art music. It reads like one long inside joke for composition students. <br /><br />The book's strong points are its description of musical pieces (in particular I liked the multi page mediation on Reich's Psalm) and the story of Peter Els and his various loves throughout life. On the other hand, I found the framing device, in which he's being chased by police for bioterrorism, to be a bit implausible, frustrating, and boring. <br /><br />There were occasional moments of brilliance drowned in a sea of excess. I disliked the use of present tense writing, and I thought the last twenty pages were a complete letdown. </span>
