    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2593320213" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2593320213" />
    <a title="Ms.pegasus" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5015851-ms-pegasus"><img alt="Ms.pegasus" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1335705124p2/5015851.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2593320213?book_show_action=true">Nov 13, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ms.pegasus" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ms.pegasus" href="/user/show/5015851-ms-pegasus">Ms.pegasus</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/18242854-orfeo">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5015851-ms-pegasus?shelf=fiction">fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2593320213" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8105352130196684525">Imagine your favorite piece of music. Do you feel the click of a metronome? Or does the experience of rhythms and unexpected change reshape time? Powers circles backwards and forward in time in this book. He traces the life of Peter Els, a 70-year-old genius, who has spent his life pushing the boundaries of musical composition. Forced into retirement, his obsessive curiosity leads him down one final rabbit hole — encoding a composition into the genes of a common household bacteria. Musical immor</span>
  <span id="freeText8105352130196684525" style="display:none">Imagine your favorite piece of music. Do you feel the click of a metronome? Or does the experience of rhythms and unexpected change reshape time? Powers circles backwards and forward in time in this book. He traces the life of Peter Els, a 70-year-old genius, who has spent his life pushing the boundaries of musical composition. Forced into retirement, his obsessive curiosity leads him down one final rabbit hole — encoding a composition into the genes of a common household bacteria. Musical immortality not just through reproduction, but through the renewal expressed in billions of mutations — it's a crackpot experiment but as harmless and threatening as John Cage's conceptual revolt. The story is told not only with frequent brief flashbacks, but stories within stories about composers and compositions that reflect Els's own emotional maturing. Powers shifts effortlessly between past tense and present tense the way a lens shifts in and out of close-up, creating context rather than chronology. One of the most compelling sections is the story of Olivier Messiaen's death camp creation of the <u>Quartet for the End of Time.</u> It's a story from the past narrated in the present tense.<br /><br />Through a cascade of errors, Els becomes a “person of interest” to Homeland Security. He flees in panic, but his flight morphs into a pilgrimage through his past. Illinois where he attended school and was swept up in avant-garde experiment, St. Louis where his ex-wife Maddy lives, Phoenix where his one-time collaborator Richard Bonner is undergoing experimental treatment, and California where his daughter Sara lives become compulsive errands of penitence and redemption.<br /><br />The people in Els's life are used by Powers as thematic material. We perceive how they change through Els's changing and painfully subjective perceptions. The most poignant of these themes is that of a precocious cellist, Clara Reston, who whispers the mysteries of Zemlinsky and Mahler like some Delphic oracle and turns him from a career in chemistry to a career in music. <br /><br />Turning from intimate to epic, Powers describes a collaboration with Richard Bonner. It is as turgid, hopelessly utopian and unbound as its inspiration, Nikolai Fedorov, whose provocative claims for human perfectibility and science-enabled immortality have undergone a disturbing revival with cloning technology. The project, a kind of choreographed oratorio is called “Immortality for Beginners.” A reviewer praises the production as fresh and original; it is also unlistenable, apparently, since he cut out an hour and a half into the performance. Els himself dubs it <i> “a vigorous corpse flower.”</i> (p.215) The metaphor is particularly apt. This is the project that ended his marriage and alienated him from his daughter.<br /> <br />Els is transformed through a progression of musical epiphanies. At age ten he is awakened by Mozart's Jupiter Symphony. In 1959 at 19 he connects with the irony of foretold grief in Mahler's <u>Kindertotenlider</u>. In 1963 as an ambitious graduate student he embraces and then rejects Samuel Barber's <u>Hermit</u> <u>Songs</u> with youthful hubris: <i> “Music wasn't about learning to love. It was about learning what to disown and when to disown it.”</i> (p.90) He hears Bob Dylan's <u>Desolation</u> <u>Row</u> in an off-campus coffeehouse and takes his great leap into the unknown. Steve Reich's <u>Proverb</u> not only feels to Els like a recapitulation of his life, but the final slowly stretched out melody is given a visual representation that recalls Ezra Pound's concrete or shape poetry (Pound's "Immorality" was the text for Els's chanson wedding gift to Maddy on her remarriage). Shostakovich's <u>Fifth</u> <u>Symphony</u> provokes a reminder of the composer's own choices between art and survival. <br /><br />The events of the real world form a backdrop of recitative to this narrative. Sputnik (1959), the Kennedy Assassination (1963), Waco (1993), Oklahoma City (1995), the Twin Towers (2001). The events form a trajectory of fear made explicit by an inserted commentary which reads like a program note: <i> “Insecurity will always be a growth industry. The economy now depends on fear.”</i> (p.228) The book was published in 2014, but resonates with a prescient urgency. <br /><br />Powers succeeds in creating a multi-faceted masterpiece. Els's subjective and often unreliable perceptions create surprise. A humorous section on famous musical dogs feels like a scherzo. The intensity he brings to his descriptions of key musical pieces will send readers, even those unfamiliar with 20th century compositions, rushing to actually hear the pieces. Paradoxical metaphors interrupt our assumptions. This is not an easy book, but it is one of the most rewarding.</span>
  <a data-text-id="8105352130196684525" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

