    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_879753677" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/879753677" />
    <a title="Mmars" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2243098-mmars"><img alt="Mmars" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1337885673p2/2243098.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/879753677?book_show_action=true">Mar 12, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Mmars" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Mmars" href="/user/show/2243098-mmars">Mmars</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2243098-mmars?shelf=music-in-fiction">music-in-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer879753677" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11086948784280860360">Every now and then you read a book that touches upon your life in a way that no other book has. So it was for me with Richard Powers&apos; &quot;Orfeo&quot;. No, I&apos;ve never been on the lam. And my scientific skills on a scale of 1 to 10 are about a 2, so a home biology lab is most definitely out of the question. <br/><br/>But....the parallels to the arc of my musical youth! The physical sensations of what music did (and still does to me). The hearing of the notes...playing that key on the keyboard and having it lead to </span>
  <span id="freeText11086948784280860360" style="display:none">Every now and then you read a book that touches upon your life in a way that no other book has. So it was for me with Richard Powers' "Orfeo". No, I've never been on the lam. And my scientific skills on a scale of 1 to 10 are about a 2, so a home biology lab is most definitely out of the question. <br /><br />But....the parallels to the arc of my musical youth! The physical sensations of what music did (and still does to me). The hearing of the notes...playing that key on the keyboard and having it lead to an infinity of sounds. Going to college the nowhere of the western midwest and finding a class on atonal music the most interesting course in four years of courses. Being there when they purchased their first synthesizer (monotonal) then composing and recording a work (if you want to call it that) for a concert. A very tedious and primitive process at the time. Loving any music that could shock and push buttons. Oh, the rebellion of it! (Overall, I've mellowed.) <br /><br />So, for the first third of the book I was entranced. I listened to Messian's "Quartet for the End of Time" three times during the chapter covering it. Imagine writing and performing music in a WWII concentration camp. I listened to the Eno. Rather normal to me. Reviewers that say knowledge of music is helpful are right. He goes deep. But for me, this book provided one of the best combinations of reading while listening to music ever! Thank you Richard Powers. <br /><br />Then there's the germ of an idea that can change a life. That happened to me. It was something I ran across in my teens. And like Els, I realize now it was not the best thing to hang my life on, but I did. I'll keep it to myself. <br /><br />But my brain had difficulty grasping the end of the book. I didn't get his experiments trying to infuse music into the human DNA. And I felt Powers writing jumped beyond the deep end as Els mind deraveled. <br /><br />Perhaps my biggest criticism is that Powers relented to having Els visit everyone important to his life while he hopscotched across the country on the good graces of a friend. What an ordinary way to wrap it up. Too bad. <br /><br />That said, this is the first Powers I have read and it won't be the last. He's an acrobatic writer. He twists thoughts, throws in offbeat tidbits, puts together unexpected words, he wows the thorough reader. The writing gets a 5. The story a 3. Enjoyment factor.....4 on the GR scale.</span>
  <a data-text-id="11086948784280860360" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


