<div id="review_2587804819" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2587804819" />
    <a title="Anna" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1991298-anna"><img alt="Anna" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1528559847p2/1991298.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2587804819?book_show_action=true">May 10, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Anna" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Anna" href="/user/show/1991298-anna">Anna</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1991298-anna?shelf=contemporary">contemporary</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1991298-anna?shelf=own-and-read">own-and-read</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1991298-anna?shelf=read-in-2019">read-in-2019</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1991298-anna?shelf=booker-prizes">booker-prizes</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2587804819" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7383033680497174550"><b>“<i>Even the slightest tune sounded like a story. Melody played on the brain like a weather report, an avowal of faith, gossip, a manifesto. The tale came across, clearer than words. But there was no tale.</i>”</b><br/><br/>I have a soft spot for art and music in fiction and here’s so much of that: writing, performing, and listening to classical music, including technical language which my snobbish self enjoys so much. The structure of the novel has something of the opera’s theatricality: it doesn’t always make for </span>
  <span id="freeText7383033680497174550" style="display:none"><b>“<i>Even the slightest tune sounded like a story. Melody played on the brain like a weather report, an avowal of faith, gossip, a manifesto. The tale came across, clearer than words. But there was no tale.</i>”</b><br /><br />I have a soft spot for art and music in fiction and here’s so much of that: writing, performing, and listening to classical music, including technical language which my snobbish self enjoys so much. The structure of the novel has something of the opera’s theatricality: it doesn’t always make for an effortless reading experience, but the dry humour somehow keeps it all together. <br /><br />Richard Powers creates in Peter Els a compelling protagonist, whose obsessions and exquisite musical sensibilities are much more interesting than the life he lives.<br /><blockquote>“What was it about music’s obsession with Faust? Spohr, Berlioz, Schumann, Gounod, Boito, Liszt, Busoni, and Mahler, down through Prokofiev, Schnittke, Adams, and Radiohead. Centuries of bad conscience, long before the Nazis burnt the temple of High Music to the ground.<br /><br />It seemed to Els (…) that classical music’s real crime was not its cozy relations with fascism but its ancient dream of control, of hot-wiring the soul. He pictured Faust looking at his own neurons on a monitor—his bottomless hunger laid bare, his desire for mastery swirling through his brain like cigarette smoke curling in the air. As full knowledge filled the seeker at last, Mephistopheles, at his elbow, would sing, <i>Now we’re both paid in full</i>.”</blockquote><br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="7383033680497174550" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

<tr class="no_border feedFooterReview" id="update_comment_stuff_Review2587804819">
